1️⃣ Start with a clean structure

Check the PDB for missing residues, missing atoms, or alternate conformations.
Fix missing hydrogens: force fields need them.
Remove unwanted molecules: crystallographic waters, ligands not part of your study, ions that aren’t physiological.
Make sure you have no Post-translational modification (PTM) in your protein because the pipeline cannot support it so reverse the modification if u know the initial amino acid. 
Tools: PyMOL, Chimera, or pdb2gmx for GROMACS.

2️⃣ Choose the right force field

Common choices for proteins: AMBER99SB-ILDN, CHARMM36, OPLS-AA.
For ligands, use ACPYPE, Antechamber (AMBER), or CGenFF (CHARMM) to generate parameters.
Avoid mixing incompatible force fields — this can cause huge forces and LINCS failures.
I recommand preparing your ligand in CGENFF *https://cgenff.com/* (create an accout using your professional email)

3️⃣ Check ligand topology early

Validate charges, atom types, and bond lengths before merging with protein.
Run a short EM on the ligand alone to make sure parameters are reasonable.
Avoid using ligands with unparameterized functional groups — GROMACS will explode otherwise.

4️⃣ Use a buffer around your system

Protein-ligand complex should be at least 1 nm away from box edges.
Too small a box → protein interacts with its own periodic image → artifacts.

5️⃣ Solvate carefully

Overlapping waters → EM fails with LINCS warnings.
Check that the system doesn’t have atoms closer than ~0.2–0.3 nm after solvation.

6️⃣ Neutralize and set ionic strength

Use genion to add ions: neutralize and optionally mimic physiological conditions (~0.15 M NaCl).
Avoid skipping this step — charge imbalance can destabilize EM.

7️⃣ Energy minimization before MD

Always do EM first — never jump straight to MD.
Disable constraints initially if the system is badly strained.
Check max force: should be < 1000 kJ/mol/nm (smaller is better).
Avoid running MD with astronomically high forces — your log shows 10¹⁸ kJ/mol forces → system will explode.

8️⃣ Check for structural issues

Visualize the system after EM: Any overlapping atoms?/ Bonds extremely stretched?/ Ligand properly positioned in binding site?
Small issues initially lead to huge MD failures later.

9️⃣ Short equilibration before production MD

Use NVT (constant volume) and NPT (constant pressure) runs before long MD.
Avoid going straight to production MD — sudden temperature or pressure changes can destroy your system.

1️⃣0️⃣ Keep an eye on time step and constraints

2 fs is standard for constrained hydrogens.
Do not constrain bonds until EM is stable.
Avoid using large time steps in initial EM — system may blow up.

1️⃣1️⃣ Automate but validate

Pipelines like CHARMM for ligands + GROMACS scripts for EM/MD save time.
But always inspect the generated topologies, box, water, and ion distribution.
Avoid blindly trusting automated scripts — they sometimes produce bad topologies for complex ligands.

1️⃣2️⃣ Document and version

Keep all .mdp files, ligand parameters, and EM outputs.
This saves hours of debugging when something goes wrong.
Avoid overwriting original structures — keep checkpoints.

Do this is a quick sanity checklist before running MD:

Protein + ligand cleaned, hydrogens added.
Ligand parameters validated.
Box large enough (~1 nm buffer).
Solvent and ions properly added.
Energy minimized without crazy forces.
Short equilibration (NVT → NPT) stable.
Forces, temperature, and pressure checked.
Checkpoints and logs saved.
